urs introduced new technologies new business models and new norms of interaction the subsequent transformation of japan's telecommunications sector was dramatic providing consumers with not only fast and sophisticated services but also low prices and an entire new ecosystem of mobile content a considerable departure from japan's long track record of being known as producer rather than consumer oriented with consumers enjoying high end services and products but at high prices yet these transformative entrepreneurs were not acting in a vacuum regulatory shifts in telecommunications were critical in providing opportunities for entrepreneurs while simultaneously protecting them from large incumbent firms these regulatory shifts were driven by the political dynamics of the 1990s as japan struggled through its post bubble economic malaise and political changes download pdf+ go to site external http ssjj oxfordjournals org cont parent research japan's transforming political economy japan studies program project topics business entrepreneurship japan search fsi search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages publications of interest leading without followers how politics and market dynamics trapped innovations in japan's domestic galapagos telecommunications sector kenji kushida journal of industry competition and trade 2011 html+ cover telecommunications reform in india rafiq dossani praeger 2002 buy+ cover illicit trafficking in the southern tier and turkey since 1999 a shift from europe l zaitseva cisac 2002 pdf+ china's telecommunications present and future yunpeng hao cisac 1997 pdf+ support map & directions contact rss+ rss xml feeds freeman spogli institute for international studies encina hall 616 serra st stanford ca 94305 6055 tel 650 723 4581 fax 650 725 2592 mail code 6055
